<tt>Tue Dec  9  6:40:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chaplain Phillip Nichols<br><br>
I had the good fortune to serve with Chaplain Phillip Nichols in the Americal Division in 1970.<br><br>
There are stories of chaplains who performed hurried worship<br>
services in the field while a chopper circled overhead - waiting to whisk them back to the rear area. I witnessed this happening one time.<br><br>
Chaplain Nichols was not like that. In fact, he accompanied the different infantry companies of our battalion on operations in the field. He stayed for days at a time. He also made trips to LZ Stinson to perform memorial services. He attempted to cheer us by bringing along his guitar.<br><br>
Chaplain Nichols was an unlikely looking soldier. For lack of a better description, he looked like a chaplain! Fair skinned with soft hands. He probably had the &quot;greenest&quot; uniform and the newest looking boots.<br><br>
It was during an operation with one of our sister companies (either Alpha or Bravo) that he was killed, along with several others, by a land mine.<br><br>
A story I heard was that prior to his last trip to the field, he tried to call his wife from the Mars Station in Chu Lai, but couldn't get through.<br><br>
I often think of how special it would have been if his wife had known.<br><br>
Phillip Nichols gave his life in  service to  his fellow man.<br><br>
